articles.title: JANUARY 1989
articles.summary: This document outlines the scheduled activities for an astronomy club during January and early February 1989. It includes details for general meetings, board meetings, and several star parties at various parks. A key event is a general meeting on January 14th featuring a presentation on the U.S. Space Station Project, with another general meeting in February discussing the Very Large Array, and an introductory observational astronomy class also starting in February.

articles.title: FIELD OF VIEW
articles.summary: This article announces two upcoming events: the 13th Annual Photo Fair, a large photographic swap meet on the West Coast featuring antique to contemporary gear, held in Santa Clara County, and Astrophoto VIII, an all-day seminar and exhibition in Orange County on February 25, 1989, for amateur astrophotographers to share techniques, view new equipment, and showcase their work.

articles.title: Seminar Information
articles.summary: This document announces the "Astrophoto VIII" seminar and exhibition, highlighting cash prizes for astrophotography categories. The deadline for papers and entries is January 15, 1989, and a $20 registration fee includes a procedure book. Participants are asked to send registration checks with their contact information to the provided Orange, CA address.

articles.title: NO SMOKING
articles.summary: Effective January 1, 1989, the building will officially become a "No Smoking" area, following a directive from the Red Cross. This policy change is anticipated to have minimal impact, as current smokers already use outdoor spaces.

articles.title: GRAZE REPORT
articles.summary: The November 30, 1988 lunar graze of Regulus was a great success, with observations made through thickening fog at Crow's Landing and under clear skies in the East Bay, Nevada, and Texas. Despite varied weather conditions, numerous observers successfully witnessed the event, and the resulting profile is anticipated for future publication.

articles.title: ELECTIONS, BOARD OF DIRECTORS
articles.summary: Five members of the Board of Directors are up for election or re-election at the upcoming February meeting. All current members whose terms are expiring are standing for re-election, and additional nominations will be accepted during the election. Four other directors will continue their terms for another year.

articles.title: BOOK PURCHASES
articles.summary: SJAA members can purchase Sky Publishing Company publications at a 20% discount by ordering through Treasurer Jack Peterson. Jack stocks some items like the Tirion Atlas and Uranometria 2000.0, and special orders others, requesting advance payment for expensive or specialized items. He also has the RASC Observer's Handbook for 1989 available.

articles.title: INTRODUCTORY ASTRONOMY CLASS RESUMES
articles.summary: The Introductory Observational Astronomy class, led by Jack Zeiders, is resuming on February 18th, offering free monthly sessions open to all. The curriculum covers a range of topics including constellation recognition, telescope use, astrophotography, and deep-sky observing, complemented by field trips to a planetarium and observatories, and presentations from guest speakers.

articles.title: THE EYE-ON-THE-SKY MAN, SHILOH UNRUH, UISITS SJAA
articles.summary: Shiloh Unruh, Lick Observatory Historian, presented on the giant refractor atop Mt. Hamilton at the San Jose Astronomical Association's (SJAA) November General Meeting, attracting approximately 60 attendees. The report also previews an upcoming article on this topic in the trade press and a December presentation by Dr. Randolfo Pozos covering the controversial 'Face on Mars,' who substituted for Richard Hoagland.

articles.title: NEW GENERAL MEETING DATES
articles.summary: The organization is changing its General Meeting date from the first Saturday of the month to the second Saturday. This adjustment aims to prevent scheduling conflicts with New Moon star parties, allowing both types of events to proceed without interference.

articles.title: BY: RICHARD STANTON
articles.summary: This article provides an astronomical observer's guide for January, detailing two meteor showers: the minor Coma Berenicids and the major Quadrantids, which peaks on January 2nd. It also lists specific observation times (PST) for various transits, eclipses, and occultations of Jupiter's Galilean moons throughout the month. Additionally, it presents a deep-sky challenge to visually detect the Flaming Star Nebula (IC 405) in Auriga.

articles.title: ASTRO ADS
articles.summary: This document is a collection of classified advertisements from late 1988, primarily featuring used astronomical equipment for sale. It includes various telescopes such as refractors, Newtonian reflectors, and Schmidt-Cassegrains from brands like Celestron and Meade, along with numerous accessories like mounts, eyepieces, and filters. The ads also contain specific 'wanted' requests for certain telescope models and issues of Telescope Making magazine, providing contact information and pricing for each listing.

articles.title: THE GREAT RED SPOT OF JUPITER BY: JIM VAN NULAND
articles.summary: Jim Van Nuland reports on recent observations of Jupiter's Great Red Spot (GRS), noting the absence of previously seen white ovals. He addresses discrepancies in GRS transit prediction times across publications, explaining his predictions account for longitudinal drift and include a random 'anti-anticipation factor' (0-3 minutes) to deter premature timing calls. These adjusted predictions indicate when the GRS is directly facing Earth, with unadjusted times available upon request for serious observers.

articles.title: Great Red Spot on Meridian PST
articles.summary: This document provides a detailed schedule of predicted dates and times when Jupiter's Great Red Spot will be on the central meridian. These timings are specifically for observers in the Pacific Standard Time (PST) zone, covering events from late December through early February. This information is highly useful for astronomers planning observation sessions to view the GRS.

articles.title: SHUTTLE ORBITER ATLANTIS RETURNS FROM SECRET MISSION
articles.summary: Space Shuttle Atlantis returned to Edwards AFB on December 6 after a 5-day secret mission, then transported back to Cape Canaveral. The orbiter sustained unusually heavy tile damage, estimated at 125-175 tiles needing replacement, likely due to ice impact during launch. Despite the damage, its next mission, launching the Magellan spacecraft to Venus on April 28, 1989, is not expected to be delayed.

articles.title: DISCOVERY TO FLY NEXT
articles.summary: The Space Shuttle Discovery is slated for its next launch on February 18th. The mission will involve deploying a TDRS satellite, for which the first stage of an Inertial Upper Stage booster will be attached.

articles.title: DOUBLE, TRIPLE, AND MULTIPLE STARS BY: PATRICK DONNELLY
articles.summary: The replacement of TDRS is delayed until late December after a technician accidentally damaged the upper stage's nozzle cone on December 1. The incident caused a 3-inch split in the carbon-carbon material of the cone, necessitating a repair or replacement.

articles.title: SOVIETS BUILDING ORBITAL INFRASTRUCTURE
articles.summary: The article details significant advancements in the Soviet space program, highlighting a large new module for the MIR space station, scheduled for launch in April 1989, which will nearly double its internal volume. It also covers the development of improved Progress and Soyuz transport vehicles, the unveiling of the world's largest transport airplane, Mria, and provides detailed specifications and comparisons of the new Soviet shuttle with its U.S. counterpart.

articles.title: EUROPEANS SELECT TITAN PROBE FOR NEXT SCIENCE PROJECT
articles.summary: The European Space Agency (ESA) has chosen a Titan probe as its next science mission. This probe will be deployed from the U.S. Saturn orbiter, Cassini, which is slated for a 1996 launch and will reach Saturn in late 2002. The Cassini mission is expected to collect data until 2006.

articles.title: GAMMA RAYS INTERFERING WITH SCIENCE SATELLITES
articles.summary: Gamma rays emitted by nuclear reactors aboard Soviet radar ocean reconnaissance satellites are interfering with science satellites, specifically impacting gamma ray detectors like those on the Solar Maximum Mission satellite. This interference, known for several years, has only recently been declassified.

articles.title: DOUBLE, TRIPLE, AND MULTIPLE STARS BY: PATRICK DONNELLY
articles.summary: This article serves as an observing guide for amateur astronomers, detailing numerous double, triple, and multiple star systems within the constellation Orion. It highlights famous targets like the Trapezium (Theta 1 Orionis), Rigel, and Zeta Orionis, providing magnitudes, separations, and viewing tips. The author encourages observers to explore these less-frequently emphasized targets during their Orion observations.

articles.title: COMET COMMENTS BY: DON MACHHOLZ
articles.summary: Comet activity is currently low, with no bright returning comets anticipated until mid-1989, emphasizing the importance of new discoveries for observation. The article details the recent discovery of Periodic Comet Ge-Wang (1988o) by Ge and Q. Wang, a 17th magnitude object found on November 4th with an 11.4-year orbit, which is not expected to brighten further.

articles.title: SEEKING COMETS
articles.summary: This article discusses trends in comet discovery, focusing on whether comets are found more often in the morning or evening sky. It references a 1967 study by Dr. Edgar Everhart, which found that 60% of long-period comets were discovered in the morning sky, despite 75% being initially discoverable there. The author also shares findings from their own study of visually-found comets, noting an increase in the percentage of discoverable comets being found in recent years.

articles.title: Comet Discovery Data (January 1975 - November 1988)
articles.summary: This document presents an analysis of 44 comets visually discovered by amateur astronomers between January 1975 and November 1988. It details statistical differences between morning and evening sky discoveries, noting that morning comets are often brighter, faster, and more likely to be retrograde, with 60% of all discoveries occurring in the morning sky. The data also reveals patterns regarding discovery locations and the timing of perihelion.

articles.title: GENERAL MEETINGS
articles.summary: The SJAA holds monthly General Meetings at the Red Cross building in Los Gatos, California, on the first Saturday of each month. These meetings feature guest speakers on diverse astronomical topics, serve as "Indoor Star Parties" for members to share interests, and foster a friendly atmosphere for enthusiasts of astrophotography, deep-sky observation, or telescope making. The document also provides detailed directions and timing for attendees.

articles.title: INDOOR STAR PARTIES
articles.summary: Indoor Star Parties are informal Saturday evening gatherings for amateur astronomers to socialize, discuss astronomy, and share equipment. Attendees are encouraged to bring telescopes and accessories, with activities ranging from outdoor observing and astrophotography slide shows to club board meetings and introductory astronomy workshops.

articles.title: FIELD EXPEDITIONS
articles.summary: The San Jose Astronomical Association (SJAA) regularly hosts "Star Parties" on New Moon Saturdays for astronomical observation at various locations, including Yosemite and primarily Fremont Peak State Park. Fremont Peak, a popular site 70 miles south of San Jose, attracts many amateur astronomers for serious deep-sky observing and astrophotography, with 50-100 telescopes commonly seen during summer New Moon weekends. The article also provides detailed directions to Fremont Peak and lists contact information for SJAA officers and board members, along with details about their monthly publication, EPHEMERIS.

articles.title: SAN JOSE ASTRONOMICAL ASSOCIATION MEMBERSHIP APPLICATION
articles.summary: This document is a membership application form for the San Jose Astronomical Association (SJAA), detailing various membership options including standard, standard with Sky & Telescope magazine, and junior memberships, along with their respective fees. It provides instructions for submitting the application and payment to the SJAA treasurer, including contact information and payment details.
